<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09117e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09117e">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09117e"> 117(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> talio esto</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Roman Law&rdquo;: The original purpose <font color="green">[of a peace-offering to the kinsmen of a thief caught and killed in the act]</font> must have been to stay the blood revenge, but in the Tables it can only have been intended to stay the prosecution which it was incumbent on the kinsmen of a murdered man to institute. So with talionic penalties: &ldquo;si membrum rupit ni cum eo pacit, <mark>talio esto</mark>&rdquo; &mdash; such, according to Gellius, were the words of the laws of the Tables, and they undoubtedly recognize talion, &ldquo;an eye for an eye, a tooth for a tooth&rdquo;; <small> <cite a>&ldquo;ROMAN LAW&rdquo;</cite></a> <a name="EBRL1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRL1"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) XXIII p. 538</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
